👉 Calendar class in Java
The Calendar class in Java is used to handle date and time operations like:
    Getting current date/time
    Adding or subtracting days/months/years
    Finding day, month, year separately
    Comparing dates

It belongs to the package:  import java.util.Calendar;

👉 Why Use Calendar?
Before Java introduced the modern Date-Time API (LocalDate, LocalTime), Calendar was commonly used because:
    Date class had many limitations
    Calendar allows modification of dates and times

👉 Creating a Calendar Object
Calendar is an abstract class, so object is created using:  Calendar c = Calendar.getInstance();

👉 Example :

import java.util.Calendar;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Calendar c = Calendar.getInstance();
        System.out.println(c);
    }
}

👉 Getting Current Date & Time

import java.util.Calendar;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Calendar c = Calendar.getInstance();
        System.out.println("Current Date : " + c.getTime());
    }
}

Output : Current Date : Sun May 11 10:30:45 IST 2026

👉 Important Methods of Calendar

| Method      | Work                       |
| ----------- | -------------------------- |
| `get()`     | Gets specific value        |
| `set()`     | Sets value                 |
| `add()`     | Adds value                 |
| `getTime()` | Returns complete date/time |
| `clear()`   | Clears values              |

👉 Getting Day, Month, Year

import java.util.Calendar;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Calendar c = Calendar.getInstance();

        int day = c.get(Calendar.DATE);
        int month = c.get(Calendar.MONTH);
        int year = c.get(Calendar.YEAR);

        System.out.println("Day : " + day);
        System.out.println("Month : " + (month + 1));
        System.out.println("Year : " + year);
    }
}
